# Enforcement Map — `enforcement.yaml`

The enforcement map is the **mechanical counterpart** to the prose enforcement
report from SKILL.md step 10b. It maps each verified property to the evidence
that proves the property is enforced — assertion names in the model, call sites
and exit codes in the code, phrases in the spec/skill text, and test names that
exercise it.

`check_enforcement.py` walks the YAML and fails CI if any claimed evidence is
missing. The prose report describes the audit; this artifact proves it.

## Why this artifact exists

Prose enforcement reports drift. A reviewer (or LLM) writes "this property is
enforced at `executing.py`, `report.py`, `finished.py`, and `heartbeat.py`" —
and a year later three of those files still enforce it but `heartbeat.py` quietly
lost the check during a refactor. The model still passes. The report still says
"enforced." The system has a hole.

The YAML closes that gap by being **executable**: every claim it makes is checked
on every commit. A drifted gate becomes a CI failure, not a documentation lie.

## Where to put it

Default location: **`./system-models/reports/enforcement.yaml`** (alongside the
prose `*-enforcement.md` reports, since the YAML is the input the prose report
is rendered from).

Run from the project root:

```bash
bash ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/verify.sh \
  --check-enforcement system-models/reports/enforcement.yaml
```

Add `--check-coverage` to also flag any model `check Foo` that has no
enforcement entry — this catches "the model proves X but no one ever wrote down
how X is enforced."

## Schema

A YAML file with a top-level `properties:` list, plus optional `tests_glob:`.
Each property entry has the shape below; all sections are optional, but a
property needs at least one gate to be useful.

```yaml
# system-models/reports/enforcement.yaml
tests_glob: tests/**/test_*.py    # optional, default shown

properties:
  - id: sticky_chain_coherence    # short stable identifier
    description: Sticky-bound tasks reject operations from the wrong context_id
    models:
      - file: planning.als
        asserts: [StickyChainCoherence, StickyBindingOnlyAtClaim]
      - file: planning_sticky_rebinding.als
        asserts: [SR1, SR2, SR3, SR4, SR5]
    code_gates:
      - {file: skills/pm/scripts/executing.py, must_call: store.check_sticky_eligibility, must_exit: 10}
      - {file: skills/pm/scripts/report.py,    must_call: store.check_sticky_eligibility, must_exit: 10}
      - {file: skills/pm/scripts/finished.py,  must_call: store.check_sticky_eligibility, must_exit: 10}
      - {file: skills/pm/scripts/heartbeat.py, must_call: store.check_sticky_eligibility, must_exit: 10}
    skill_texts:
      - file: skills/pm/executing/SKILL.md
        must_mention: ["sticky", "exit 10"]
    tests: [G8, G46s, G47, G48]
```

### Field semantics

| Field | Check |
|---|---|
| `id` | Free-form short identifier. Used in output; should be stable. |
| `description` | Human-readable summary. Shown in the report. |
| `models[].file` | Path to a `.als` or `.dfy` file (relative to project root). |
| `models[].asserts` | For `.als`: each name must appear as `assert <name>` AND have a paired `check <name>`. For `.dfy`: each must appear as `lemma <name>` or `method <name>`. |
| `code_gates[].file` | Path to source file (relative to project root). |
| `code_gates[].must_call` | A function/method the file must call. Python files use AST (matches dotted names like `store.check_sticky_eligibility` and bare-name imports). Other languages use a regex fallback (`<tail>(`) and emit a `(regex fallback — non-Python)` note. |
| `code_gates[].must_exit` | An integer exit code the file must produce via `return N`, `sys.exit(N)`, `exit(N)`, or `raise SystemExit(N)`. |
| `skill_texts[].file` | Path to a markdown / spec / instruction file. |
| `skill_texts[].must_mention` | List of phrases (case-insensitive substring). All must appear. |
| `tests` | List of test names. Searched as `def [test_]<name>\b` across files matching `tests_glob`. |

### Pass/fail rule

A property passes only when **every** gate listed under it passes. Each failed
gate produces a separate red row in the output with a brief diagnostic. The
checker exits 0 if every property passes, 1 if any property fails.

## Output

Default text mode prints a per-property table:

```
======================================================================
 Enforcement audit — 2/3 properties pass
======================================================================

✓ idempotent_finalize — finalize is idempotent
  ✓ planning.als: assert IdempotentFinalize
  ✓ scripts/finished.py: calls store.mark_done
  ✓ scripts/finished.py: exits with 0
  ✓ tests: def idempotent_finalize_twice

✗ sticky_chain_coherence — Sticky-bound tasks reject wrong context_id
  ✓ planning.als: assert StickyChainCoherence
  ✓ scripts/executing.py: calls store.check_sticky_eligibility
  ✓ scripts/report.py: calls store.check_sticky_eligibility
  ✗ scripts/heartbeat.py: calls store.check_sticky_eligibility  (no matching call expression)
  ✓ scripts/finished.py: calls store.check_sticky_eligibility

FAIL — 1 property failed
```

`--format json` emits the same data as a structured object suitable for CI
scrapers or dashboards. Each property has `id`, `description`, `ok`, and a
`gates[]` list of `{label, ok, detail}`.

## Authoring guidance

**Build the entry alongside the model, not after.** When you add a `check Foo`
to a `.als` file because the user cares about property X, immediately add the
matching `enforcement.yaml` entry — even if you only know one of the gates yet.
The empty fields are honest: "we proved X, we don't yet know where it's
enforced." That signal is more useful than a polished prose report written
months later from grep output.

**One entry per property, not per gate.** A property enforced at four sites is
one entry with four `code_gates` rows, not four entries. The id should describe
the *thing being protected*, not the protection mechanism.

**Use `tests` even if the test isn't great.** A weak test that exercises the
gate is still an early warning if the gate disappears. The checker doesn't
evaluate test quality — only presence.

**Don't use `must_mention` as a substitute for `must_call`.** A skill text that
says "the system rejects X" is a *claim*, not a *check*. If the rejection is
implemented in code, mark the code gate; reserve `skill_texts` for protocols
where the text *is* the enforcement (LLM checklists, human runbooks).

## What this still won't catch

- **Wrong predicate in the model.** If `assert Foo` proves the wrong thing, the
  checker can't help — it only verifies that the named assertion exists.
- **Wrong call target.** If the gate calls `store.check_sticky_eligibility`
  but that function is a stub returning `True`, the checker passes. The
  model + tests catch this; the enforcement map only proves wiring.
- **Non-protocol issues.** Friction, ergonomics, defaults, integration shape —
  all outside what formal modeling addresses, and outside what this checker
  addresses.

The map closes the "claim doesn't match implementation wiring" class.
Everything else stays the responsibility of the model, the tests, and review.
